{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476983"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:55:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:55:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14110"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14110"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.76,0.04,0.07,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92556"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6790"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75871"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1842"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6281"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44195"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92556"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with her mother. The mother reports that while walking in the park, the child suddenly started crying and refused to use her left arm. This occurred immediately after the parent had grabbed the child\u0027s arm to prevent her from running into the road. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well but distressed. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She holds her left arm slightly flexed at the elbow and pronated. She refuses to use the arm and cries when it is manipulated. There is no visible swelling or deformity. An X-ray of the elbow shows no abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supracondylar fracture","Pulled elbow","Wrist sprain","Radial avulsion fracture","Median nerve injury"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is a \u003Cstrong\u003Epulled elbow\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as nursemaid\u0027s elbow or radial head subluxation. This condition is common in young children, typically occurring between the ages of one and four years. The mechanism of injury often involves a sudden pull or yank on the child\u0027s arm, as described in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe classic presentation of a pulled elbow includes sudden onset of pain, refusal to use the affected arm, and holding the arm slightly flexed and pronated. These symptoms are all present in this case. The absence of visible swelling or deformity is also typical of a pulled elbow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esupracondylar fracture\u003C/strong\u003E of the humerus is a common elbow injury in children, but it typically results from a fall onto an outstretched hand. It would likely show visible swelling and deformity, and an abnormal X-ray, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ewrist sprain\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely to cause the child to hold her arm in the described position. Additionally, the mechanism of injury and the location of pain do not fit with a wrist sprain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial avulsion fracture\u003C/strong\u003E would be visible on X-ray and is more common in adults than in young children. The mechanism of injury for this fracture typically involves a fall onto an outstretched hand with the wrist extended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve injury\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the sudden onset of symptoms or the child\u0027s reluctance to use the entire arm. Median nerve injuries typically cause sensory and motor deficits in the hand rather than pain and limited movement of the entire arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that X-rays are typically normal in cases of pulled elbow. They are not routinely required for diagnosis but may be performed to rule out fractures if the presentation is atypical. The treatment for a pulled elbow involves a specific manoeuvre to reduce the subluxation, which usually provides immediate relief.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulled elbow (nursemaid\u0027s elbow) is a common injury in young children, typically occurring when the arm is pulled or yanked.","The classic presentation of pulled elbow includes sudden onset of pain, refusal to use the affected arm, and holding the arm slightly flexed and pronated.","X-rays are typically normal in cases of pulled elbow and are not routinely required for diagnosis."],"references":["Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Pulled elbow [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne; c2024 [cited 2024 Sep 2]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Pulled_elbow/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75871"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14110"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75871"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T12:01:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T12:01:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6790"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92556"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r